3 Application Scenarios

waterfall plotFigureYa39bar

base plotggplot2

Draw a marked time bar chart based on prognosis or treatment characteristics.

It is usually used in conjunction with waterfall plot. For the drawing method, you can refer to FigureYa39bar.

Here it is drawn using base plot. You can also try to draw it using ggplot2.

5 Input File

easy_input.csvpatient

easy_input.csv, one patient per row, containing at least three columns of time and their corresponding status.

# 
# Reading Data
dat <- read.table("easy_input.txt",sep = "\t",header = T,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,row.names = 1)
head(dat)
##    OS.time    OS PFS.time PFS New_therapy Therapy_time
## P1      30  Dead       25  DP         Yes            5
## P2      20  Dead       20  DP          No           NA
## P3      16 Alive        8  DP         Yes            8
## P4      15 Alive       15  DS     Missing           NA
## P5      13  Dead        4  DP         Yes            9
## P6      12  Dead        5  DP         Yes            7
# 
# Sort by survival time so that the legend can be displayed in the lower right corner
dat <- dat[order(dat$OS.time,decreasing = F),]

6 Start drawing

?pch/

examplebar

base plot

Which color schemes should be chosen? What shapes should be selected for special symbols? It all depends on personal or journal preferences to view the optional shapes on pch. By referring to the annotations and adjusting the parameters, you can modify it to the way you like.

Here, we take the sketch and the example provided by the demander as examples respectively. The main difference between the two lies in the adjustment of detailed parameters: coordinate axes, color, line thickness, the shape of special symbols, and the distance between special symbols and the bar.

Using base plot to draw graphs has the advantage of freedom. You can draw whatever you want.

plotplot If you want to run it in segments, run it from plot to the code you want to view. Be sure to start with plot.

6.1 draft Draw according to the draft provided by the demander

# 
# Set Colors
orange <- "#fa7921"
darkred   <- "#F2042C"
darkblue  <- "#1d00ff"
peach  <- "#E43889"

# 1. 
# 1. Open the canvas
par(bty = "o", mgp = c(1.5,.33,0), mar = c(3,3,1,2),las = 1, tcl = -.25)
plot(NULL,NULL,
     xlim = c(0,max(dat$OS.time)) + max(dat$OS.time)/10,
     ylim = c(1,nrow(dat)),
     xlab = "Time (Years)",
     ylab = "",
     yaxt = "n")
axis(side = 2,at = seq(1,nrow(dat)),labels = rownames(dat))

# 2. overall survival
# 2. Main Timeline: overall survival (Longest Time)
for (p in 1:nrow(dat)) {
  lines(c(0,dat[p,"OS.time"]),
        c(p,p),
        lwd = 5,
        col = orange)
  
  # 
  # If the patient has a new treatment and the time is available
  if(dat[p,"New_therapy"] == "Yes") {
    lines(c(dat[p,"Therapy_time"],dat[p,"OS.time"]),
          c(p,p),
          lwd = 3,
          col = peach)}
  
  # 
  # Add arrows if the patient is alive
  if(dat[p,"OS"] == "Alive") {
    Arrowhead(dat[p,"OS.time"],p,lcol = darkred,arr.type = "triangle")
  } else if(dat[p,"OS"] == "Dead") { #   # Add a block if the patient dies
    points(dat[p,"OS.time"],p,col = darkblue,pch = 15,cex = 2)
  } else if(dat[p,"OS"] == "Missing") { #  # Add a star (hexagram)
    points(dat[p,"OS.time"],p,col = "black",pch = 24,cex = 1.5,bg = "black") #   # upper triangle
    points(dat[p,"OS.time"],p,col = "black",pch = 25,cex = 1.5,bg = "black") #   # lower triangle
  }
}

# 3. progression free survivalOS
# 3. Sub-timeline: progression free survival (Time falls within the OS interval)
for (p in 1:nrow(dat)) {
  # 
  # Add circles if the patient's disease progresses
  if(dat[p,"PFS"] == "DP") {
    points(dat[p,"PFS.time"],p,col = darkred,pch = 19, cex = 2)
  } else {next()}
}
## Warning in xy.coords(x, y): NAs introduced by coercion
## Warning in xy.coords(x, y): NAs introduced by coercion
# 4. AI
# 4. Draw Legends (This needs to be adjusted according to the size of the image, or it will be more convenient for AI later)
# 4.1 
# 4.1 Survival
Arrowhead(25,3.75,
          lcol = darkred,arr.type = "triangle")
text(26,3.75,"Alive",pos = 4)

# 4.2 
# 4.2 Death
filledrectangle(mid = c(25,3),
                wx = 0.2,wy = 1,
                col = darkblue,
                angle = 270)
text(26,3,"Dead",pos = 4)

# 4.3 
# 4.3 Disease Progression
points(25,2.25,col = darkred,pch = 19, cex = 2)
text(26,2.25,"DS",pos = 4)

# 4.4 
# 4.4 Lost to Follow-up
points(25,1.5,col = "black",pch = 24,cex = 1.5,bg = "black")
points(25,1.5,col = "black",pch = 25,cex = 1.5,bg = "black")
text(26,1.5,"Missing",pos = 4)

dev.copy2pdf(file = "swimmer_draft.pdf",width = 6,height = 3)

6.2 example Draw according to the example text

# 
# Set Colors
jcoBlue <- "#248EC9"
jcoYellow <- "#EDC622"
jcoRed <- "#BE5D54"

# 1. 
# 1. Open the canvas
par(bty = "o", mgp = c(1.5,.33,0), mar = c(3,3,1,2),las = 1, tcl = -.25)
plot(NULL,NULL,
     xlim = c(0,max(dat$OS.time)) + max(dat$OS.time)/10,
     ylim = c(1,nrow(dat)),
     xlab = "Time (Years)",
     ylab = "Patients With Response",
     yaxt = "n")
axis(side = 2,tck = 0, #  # Do not display the scale lines
     at = seq(1,nrow(dat)),
     labels = rep("", nrow(dat))) #ypatient   # The Y-axis does not display the patient number

# 2. overall survival
# 2. Main Timeline: overall survival (Longest Time)
for (p in 1:nrow(dat)) {
  lines(c(0,dat[p,"OS.time"]),
        c(p,p),
        lwd = 10, #  # The thickness of the lane
        col = jcoBlue)
  
  # 
  # If the patient has a new treatment and the time is available
  if(dat[p,"New_therapy"] == "Yes") {
    lines(c(dat[p,"Therapy_time"],dat[p,"OS.time"]),
          c(p,p),
          lwd = 10,
          col = jcoYellow)}
  
  # 
  # Add arrows if the patient is alive
  if(dat[p,"OS"] == "Alive") {
    Arrows(dat[p,"OS.time"] + .5, #+0.5  #If you want to leave a blank space, just add 0.5 and adjust it according to your own preference
              p, dat[p,"OS.time"] + 1.5, p, #x0, y0, x1, y1  # arrows with tails require x0, y0, x1, y1
           lcol = jcoRed, arr.col = jcoRed, # # color
           lwd = 5, arr.lwd = 1, # # thickness
           arr.length = .2, arr.width = .3, 
           arr.type = "triangle") # ?Arrows   # ? Arrows View Usage
  } else if(dat[p,"OS"] == "Dead") { #   # Add a cross if the patient dies
    points(dat[p,"OS.time"] + 1,
       p,col = jcoRed, pch = 3,
       cex = 1, #  # size
       lwd = 5, #  # thickness
       bg = jcoRed) 
  } else if(dat[p,"OS"] == "Missing") { #   # Add snowflakes if the patient is lost to follow-up
    points(dat[p,"OS.time"] + 1, 
           p, col = jcoRed, pch = 8, cex = 1.5, lwd = 3)
  }
}

# 3. progression free survivalOS
# 3. Sub-timeline: progression free survival (Time falls within the OS interval)
for (p in 1:nrow(dat)) {
  # 
  # Add circles if the patient's disease progresses
  if(dat[p,"PFS"] == "DP") {
    points(dat[p,"PFS.time"], p, col = jcoRed,
           pch = 21, lwd = 5, bg = "white",
           cex = 2)
  } else {next()}
}
## Warning in xy.coords(x, y): NAs introduced by coercion
## Warning in xy.coords(x, y): NAs introduced by coercion
# 4. AI
# 4. Draw Legends (This needs to be adjusted according to the size of the image, or it will be more convenient for AI later)

# 
# The drawing method of the special symbols is consistent with that in the above picture
# 4.1 
# 4.1 Survival
Arrows(24.7,3.75,25.5,3.75, #  # position coordinates
       lcol = jcoRed, arr.col = jcoRed, #  # color
       lwd = 5, arr.lwd = 1, #  # thickness
       arr.length = .2, arr.width = .3, 
       arr.type = "triangle")
text(26,3.75, "Alive", pos = 4)

# 4.2 
# 4.2 Death
points(25, 3, #  # position coordinates
       col = jcoRed, pch = 3,
       cex = 1, #  # size
       lwd = 5, #  # thickness
       bg = jcoRed)
text(26,3, "Dead", pos = 4)

# 4.3 
# 4.3 Disease Progression
points(25, 2.25, #  # position coordinates
       col = jcoRed,
           pch = 21, lwd = 5, bg = "white",
           cex = 2)
text(26,2.25, "DS", pos = 4)

# 4.4 
# 4.4 Lost to Follow-up
points(25, 1.5, #   # position coordinates
       col = jcoRed, pch = 8, cex = 1.5, lwd = 3)
text(26,1.5, "Missing", pos = 4)
